problem: Simplify $\dfrac{3+4i}{1+2i}$. Your answer should be of the form $a+bi$, where $a$ and $b$ are both real numbers and written as improper fractions (if necessary).
model_solution:
## Step 1: Multiply the numerator and denominator by the complex conjugate of the denominator
$\dfrac{3+4i}{1+2i} \cdot \dfrac{1-2i}{1-2i}$
## Step 2: Expand and simplify the expression
$\dfrac{3+4i}{1+2i} \cdot \dfrac{1-2i}{1-2i} = \dfrac{3(1) + 3(-2i) + 4i(1) + 4i(-2i)}{1(1) + 1(-2i) + 2i(1) + 2i(-2i)}$

$= \dfrac{3 - 6i + 4i - 8i^2}{1 - 2i + 2i - 4i^2}$
## Step 3:
$= \dfrac{3 - 6i + 4i - 8i^2}{1 - 2i + 2i - 4i^2} = \dfrac{3 - 2i + 8}{1 - 4i^2} = \dfrac{11 - 2i}{1 + 4} = \dfrac{11 - 2i}{5}$
$= \dfrac{11}{5} - \dfrac{2}{5}i$
$= \dfrac{11}{5} - \dfrac{2}{5}i$
